SIMPLE: roundelay
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Roundelay
<hw>Round"e*lay</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>rondelet</ets>, dim. of <ets>rondel</ets>. See <er>Roundel</er>,
<er>Roundeau</er>, and cf. <er>Roundlet</er>, <er>Rundlet</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Poetry)</fld> <def>See <er>Rondeau</er>, and
<er>Rondel</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A tune in which a
simple strain is often repeated; a simple rural strain which is short
and lively.</def> <au>Spenser.</au> <au>Tennyson.</au> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>A dance in a circle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything having a round form; a roundel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rounder</ent>⟦br⟧
